***Follow up actions added to [8\. Follow-ups](#bookmark=kix.z0nu9suno5j2)***

### Summary (w/c 24.11.2025)

**Order Volume declined for the second week in a row in W13 (-4% WoW) to 5,377 orders, with GTV \-2%. Our platform penetration (orders in FTT zones during window) decreased to 2.14% (vs 2.20% last week). We are attributing this to the continued unpinning of the Carousel and Mission tile which is leading to lower FTT visibility and traffic. These two merchandising elements are our largest two entry points. We will resume Mission Tile pinning after BF ends.** 

[***Proposition Performance:***](#bookmark=kix.gn9p1r3pqaxn) 

* **OV has continued to decline this week, though at a slower rate than last week, with abs new cx also declining.**   
  * Visibility and conversion remain broadly stable vs last week: visibility has ticked up marginally), but this has been offset by a small drop in conversion). This indicates that last week‚Äôs uplift in conversion was driven by a drop in the visibility denominator \- meaning a higher proportion of viewers were high-intent customers \- rather than a shift to a new, higher underlying conversion baseline \- ie conversion is unlikely to keep rising significantly WoW on its own. We need to continue pushing this proposition in front of customers and focus on educating new users to both build awareness and sustain conversion gains over time.  
  * Further supporting this, abs new cx (2.7k this week)  has been declining WoW since 27/10.   
* **Once cx engage with the proposition, indicators of its appeal are positive:**  
  * Returning-to-FTT customer and OV share and abs values continue to grow, demonstrating stickiness among existing users.  
  * Ratings have increased (4.47 vs 4.36 this time last week), driven by more 5\* orders (76% vs 71% this time last week).  
  * ‚ÄúWho Loves It‚Äù analysis confirms broad appeal across demographics, indicating the FTT offering resonates widely once experienced.  
* **Other notes:**  
  * **New-to-Brand has declined,** continuing a downward trend over the last few months. This is likely driven in part by an increasing proportion of returning cx.  
  * **Some changes in top 5 px:** Giggling has now entered the top 5 (at \#5), replacing Banana Tree. Wagamama and Pho have swapped positions with Pho now \#1.   
  * **Other indicators remain steady**  
    * Scheduled orders are flat; top-performing cuisines, and dishes remain consistent, New-to-Roo, family and location splits remain stable.  
    * High-frequency users continue to dominate.

[***Marketing:***](#bookmark=kix.opc6mn77bieg) 

**Media Insights:** The bulk of the marketing campaign activity ended on 23/11 as planned. CRM & search will continue as always-on until the end of the year and will be reported on weekly in this document. Planning for H1 2026 has commenced with the media brief due next week. 

**CRM:** This week we led with a Px selection message on email, while using push to remind customers of their last chance to enter Family Dinneroo Rewards. Push engagement dropped WoW but remained at benchmark (CTR 0.8%; \-0.3ppt WoW). Email engagement dropped below benchmark CTR 0.2% ( \-0.1ppt Wow). We will keep observing results, to understand if drop is related to value prop of FT, or seasonal as Cxs receive more comms during Black Friday week.

**DXGY:** To date, 29.6k customers have entered, up 5.3k this week, and off the back of a record week WC 17/11, where we swept up an additional 9.3k. 1.7k Cx have completed all steps \- with ¬£41.4k vouchers earned and spend at ¬£25.6k (vs total budget ¬£100k); redemption rate at 59%.

[***Operations Performance***](#bookmark=kix.ymzajtvfpqwk) ***and [Care:](#bookmark=kix.1f2uspat9ezy)*** 

**B10s:** 

* **Lowlights:** Unacceptable lates increased \+0.84ppt to 9.85% being driven by RWT reaching increasing \+1.0ppt to 6.70%.  
* **Highlights**: OI decreased to its lowest week ever \-0.54ppt WoW to 2.47% compared to non-Dinneroo orders, which dropped \-0.01ppt WoW to 1.60%. This drove an improved App rating \+0.11 pt WoW to 4.47, closing in on non-dinneroo App rating of 4.50. Wagamama had its lowest OI rate of 2.90% and Pizza Express had its lowest OI rate of 2.08% beating PEX non-dinneroo orders this week.

* **Cx Funnel \-** see [Appendix](#bookmark=kix.vdgqvp30muk7) for more detail  
  * Limited visibility continues due to the unpinned Mission Tile and Home Carousel.  
    * Mission Tile taps are down by an average of \-88%\*. (Black Friday)   
    * Home Carousel taps are down by an average of \-89%\*. (Business decision to unpin)  
    * Merch Card also experienced limited visibility over the last two weeks\*, resulting in a \-92% decrease in taps. (Black Friday)

			*\*Most recent 2 weeks (17/11/2025 \- 24/11/2025) vs 2 weeks prior (03/11/2025 \-10/11/2025)*

* The combined tap loss from these three components accounts for 64K lost taps (traffic that would have entered the funnel) over the last two weeks.  
  * This traffic is estimated to account for approximately 2.5K orders over the two weeks.  
    * The Marketing Banner is successfully offsetting some of the lost order volume. It has seen an average 108% growth in taps over the last two weeks and has driven \+400 conversions through its entry point.   
    * We have also observed conversions rising from users who did not engage with an entry point, suggesting many users can still find the proposition (e.g. via "order again" or directly visiting the partner). This is likely driven by returning customers who are already familiar with the proposition.   
      * Limited visibility will contribute to the decline in users trying FTT for the first time and will continue to stunt the propositions' growth even after the entry points are visible again.   
    * Despite this offset, we are still down by an average of \-900 conversions per week compared to two weeks prior. The loss breaks down as:  
      * Home Carousel: Accounted for 65% (584 conversions) of the weekly loss. (This is in line with [results from the XP](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1t8-G7e8C1uaLDCwzDmjsncLuiyta9NyGCtx-9RFsFpQ/edit?tab=t.0).)  
      * Mission Tile: Accounted for 29% (262 conversions) of the weekly loss.  
      * Merch Card: Accounted for 6% (54 conversions) of the weekly loss.


| ![][image1] | ![][image2] |
| :---- | :---- |

  * **Why does the Conversion Rate (CvR) appear to be increasing/performing well?**  
    * The apparent increase in CvR is due to the removal of high-visibility entry points (Mission Tile and Home Carousel). These entry points typically attract a higher volume of lower-intent customers. Their removal filters out this "noise," leaving a more concentrated pool of users who have a greater intent to purchase, therefore artificially inflating the reported CvR.  
  * **What should we action?**  
    * We have seen that the Marketing Banner can work **harder** for us when it is visible to customers without the distraction of the home carousel. Improving this component could be a key lever to decrease dependency on the Home Carousel.  
    * Based on the Mission Tile's estimated impact (262 conversions) and the observed lift in Marketing Banner performance without top-of-fold competition, we should prioritise testing the Mission Tile in position \#2, along with other positions, to understand the optimal entry point configuration. This allows us to leverage the Marketing Banner's superior conversion rate (avg 4-5% vs 2-3% Mission Tile) and larger footprint for overall proposition benefit.  
    * Session volumes on the Collection page continue to sit around 24K per week, which is similar to the beginning of the proposition. To prepare for any experimentation/improvements to the Collection page, we need to continue finding ways to direct customers directly to the page. The whatsapp link sharing idea will support this. We have provided tracking parameters to monitor its effectiveness.

* **Order Composition**  
  * **Ordering patterns** \- scheduled orders constant  
    * 18% scheduled (vs 18% last week)  
  * **Top performing brands, cuisines, dishes** \- some change in top brands, while top cuisines and dishes remain relatively constant.  
    * Top 5 brands: Giggling has now entered the top 5, and Wagamama and Pho have swapped back positions. Top 5 in order are now: Pho, Wagamama, Dishoom, PEX and Giggling. PEX and Banana Tree at lowest levels since wc 20/10.  
    * Top cuisines: Asian dominates (54% vs 55% last week), followed by Indian (14% vs 14% last week) and Italian (10% vs 11% last week)  
    * Top 3 dishes: Wags Family Chicken Katsu, Pho‚Äôs Pho the Whole Family and Dishoom‚Äôs Chicken Ruby (same as last week)  
* **Cx Composition \-** New-to-Roo is constant, while New-to Brand continues to decline. OV continues to be driven by high-frequency users, with PLUS users constant  and almost 2/3rds of users returning to the platform within 7 days). Returning-to-FTT continues to grow from a cx and OV share perspective, though abs New-to-FTT cx are down. From a demographic POV, family and location splits remain constant.    
  * **New-to-Roo Cx:** 1% cx are new-to-platform (vs 1% last week)  
  * **New-to-Brand Cx:** 28% of orders are new to brand (vs 30% last week)  
  * **PLUS / Frequent Cx:** 65% of orders are from PLUS users (vs 66% last week); 62% return to platform within 7 days (vs 61% last week)  
  * **Returning-to-FTT:**   
    * Returning to FTT cx and OV continues to rise (49% cx this week vs 46% last week, 51% OV vs 47% last week).  However, despite adding \>2.7k new customers each week, new-customer demand generation has been declining WoW since 27/10, which is increasingly concerning and should be monitored and addressed.  
    * Breaking out the Returning-to-FTT groups, we see a healthy mix of customers returning once, twice, 3 times, and 4+ times. This suggests that repeat visits aren‚Äôt just driven by a small group of super users \- the proposition is resonating broadly and encouraging a range of customers to come back.

  * Wagamama are exploring redoing photography to improve perception (likely Q1 2026\) and trialling a larger bag to solve the issue of missing items when 2+ items are in the order (as the bags can only fit 1 Dinneroo proposition dish and nothing else). Wagamama is unable to commit to an actionable date on this end of the year.   
* Banana Tree: OI 2.68%\! (+1.69 ppt WoW) non-dinneroo (1.97%). RWT spike to 10.60% (+5.60ppt WoW) and non-dinneroo (8.50%).   
  * AM returned from holiday this week, awaiting update from next week on BTG priorities.  
* Giggling Squid: OI 2.50% (-1.03ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (1.53%), RWT 3.00% (-1.9ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (1.8%)  
  * Total non-peak hour metrics up YoY. Further investigation into OI needed and will take to the partner. Team are looking at adjusting/improving the proposition mid-December.  
* Bella Italia: OI 2.74% (+0.24 ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (2.16%), RWT 11.0% (+1.0 ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (7.90%)  
  * Still awaiting AM engagement and update post return from holiday.  
* Prezzo: OI 5.56% (-4.44 ppt) vs non-dinneroo (3.33%), RWT 11.10% (+11.1ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (5.8%)  
  * Prezzo menu is going live next week (02.12), which should hopefully eliminate OI around the number of pots, but also moving to dishes that should a) resonate more with the cx b) staff should be more familiar with them  
* Xian Street Food: OI 0.00% (Flat WoW) vs non-dinneroo (1.19%) RWT 7.40% (-2.0ppt WoW) vs non-dinneroo (6.1%)  
  * Test orders showcased Xian preparing orders up to 30 mins late during peak hours from 19:30-21:30, highlighting internal kitchen preparation issues. AM to discuss these outcomes with Xian during the next meeting (date being determined)

Based on total customer comments, the most common issues are spilled or leaked items, wrong or missing orders, and poor food quality (burnt, undercooked, or not fresh).

* Pho (25+ Issues): Frequent soup and curry leaks, wrong or missing items, incorrect vegetarian/vegan substitutions, cold or stale dishes, and packaging failures during delivery.  
* Wagamama (20+ Issues): Missing or incorrect items, undercooked chicken, misleading portion sizes, spillage from poorly sealed containers, and cold or incomplete family meals.  
* Giggling Squid (15‚Äì18 Issues): Repeated curry leaks and crushed containers, wrong or contaminated items, poor packaging integrity, and missing sauces or sides.  
* PizzaExpress (10‚Äì12 Issues): Crushed or stuck pizzas, spilled sauces, bland or cold pasta, missing pesto or toppings, and inconsistent food quality.  
* Banana Tree (8‚Äì10 Issues): Frequent spillages, burnt sauces, wrong meat in dishes, poor chicken quality, and cross-contamination in vegan/vegetarian meals.  
* Dishoom (6‚Äì8 Issues): Curry leaks and spillage, missing or incorrect items, undercooked chicken, and poor packaging leading to mess and waste.  
* Bill‚Äôs (4‚Äì5 Issues): Leaking sauces, mouldy or spoiled food, cross-contamination risks, and allergic reactions from mixed ingredients.  
* TUK TUK-SGroup (3‚Äì4 Issues): Cold, delayed, or incomplete orders with spilled sauces and hard or dry chicken.  
* Farmer J (3‚Äì4 Issues): Spilled mac & cheese and broth, wrong items (tofu vs. chicken), and poor freshness.  
* Kricket (2‚Äì3 Issues): Spilled curries and greasy packaging, with contamination on delivery.  
* Cocotte (2 Issues): Wrong side item delivered and poor meal quality (cold or bland).  
* Xian Street Food (2 Issues): Open or spilled containers making meals inedible.  
* Las Iguanas (1‚Äì2 Issues): Spillage and poor packaging on delivery.  
* LEON (1‚Äì2 Issues): Missing ingredients and poor product quality.  
* Itsu (1‚Äì2 Issues): Packaging leaks and soup spills making food inedible.  
* Yacob‚Äôs Kitchen (1 Issue): Wrong product received and mismatch with description.  
* Tula Ireland (1 Issue): Broken sour cream container spilling into the order.  
* Chaska (1 Issue): Poor packing and leakage causing food contamination.  
* Others (1‚Äì2 Issues Each): Zambrero UK and similar brands ‚Äî isolated cases of spillages, wrong items, or poor food quality.
